<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,718,887]" pageId="2" pageNumber="33">
Peritremal shields with blunt posterior ends posterior to coxa IV. Two different 
<typeStatus box="[1065,1124,719,743]" pageId="2" pageNumber="33">types</typeStatus>
of setae are present on the podonotum; one of them (p 
<number box="[478,488,755,779]" pageId="2" pageNumber="33" value="1.0">1</number>
) short and smooth, other (p 
<number box="[821,836,755,779]" pageId="2" pageNumber="33" value="2.0">2</number>
) long, feathered or spiny. There is a large, weakly sclerotised area between peritremal shield and the edge of the podonotum. Adgenital shields are present, with 
<number box="[1394,1436,791,815]" pageId="2" pageNumber="33" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
opening valves. The opisthonotum has seven or eight pairs marginal setae. The anterior margin of the ventrianal shield has one or two pairs of setae (
<bibRefCitation author="Urhan" box="[558,704,862,887]" pageId="2" pageNumber="33" refString="Urhan, R. (1995) Artvin Ili Zerkonidlerinin (Acari, Mesostigmata, Zerconidae) Sistematik Yonden Incelenmesi. Ph. D. Thesis, Institute of Sciences, Erzurum Ataturk University, Erzurum, 129 pp." type="book" year="1995">
Urhan, 
<number box="[644,704,862,887]" pageId="2" pageNumber="33" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
